    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1926-06-04T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1926-06-04T05:00:00-05:00" n="62"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d62">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.51 W 89France/315: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Herrick</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-06-04T11:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 4, 1926—11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 4—8:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>224. In a telephone conversation on the evening of June 3, Bérenger stated that
                    his task of obtaining ratification of the French debt agreement would be
                    facilitated if the United States Treasury Department <pb facs="0191" n="95"
                        xml:id="pg_95"/> would raise the embargo against the firm of Boue
                        Soeurs<note n="6" xml:id="d62fn6">A Treasury Department order of Aug. 31,
                        1925, as amended Sept. 16, 1925, prohibiting, in accordance with section 510
                        of the tariff act of 1922, the importation and delivery of merchandise
                        manufactured by or for the account of Boue Soeurs, Ltd., of Paris, for
                        refusal of said firm to submit certain of its books and records for
                        inspection.</note> as a mark of good will. This firm would seem to have been
                    punished sufficiently for the faults which it may have committed heretofore, and
                    as apparently it has very powerful connections, I hope that Mr. Mellon<note
                        n="7" xml:id="d62fn7">Andrew Mellon, Secretary of the Treasury and Chairman
                        of the World War Foreign Debt Commission.</note> may see his way clear to
                    take action such as suggested by M. Bérenger. This might furthermore deter the
                    French press from outbursts against our customs representatives abroad for their
                    alleged inquisitorial methods.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Herrick</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
